=========================================
C++17 STRUCTURED BINDINGS
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What are Structured Bindings?

Structured Bindings were introduced in C++17.

They allow a single object (such as a pair, tuple, array, or struct) to be unpacked into individual variables.

Instead of accessing members using .first, .second, std::get<>(), or object.member, we can directly create named variables.

Syntax

auto [var1, var2, ...] = object;

-----------------------------------------

2. Why were Structured Bindings introduced?

Before C++17, unpacking objects was verbose.

Example

pair<int,string> p = {1,"Pavan"};

cout << p.first << endl;
cout << p.second << endl;

With C++17

auto [id, name] = p;

cout << id << endl;
cout << name << endl;

The code becomes cleaner and easier to read.

-----------------------------------------

3. Pair Example

#include <iostream>
#include <utility>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    pair<int,string> p = {1,"Pavan"};

    auto [id, name] = p;

    cout << id << endl;
    cout << name << endl;
}

Output

1
Pavan

-----------------------------------------

4. What happens internally?

pair<int,string> p = {1,"Pavan"};

auto [id,name] = p;

is roughly equivalent to

int id = p.first;
string name = p.second;

It simply creates two variables initialized from the pair.

-----------------------------------------

5. Tuple Example

tuple<int,string,double> t = {1,"Pavan",95.5};

auto [id,name,marks] = t;

cout << id << endl;
cout << name << endl;
cout << marks << endl;

-----------------------------------------

6. Array Example

int arr[] = {10,20};

auto [a,b] = arr;

cout << a << " " << b;

-----------------------------------------

7. Struct Example

struct Employee
{
    int id;
    string name;
};

Employee e{1,"Pavan"};

auto [id,name] = e;

cout << id << endl;
cout << name << endl;

-----------------------------------------

8. Map Example (Most Asked)

map<int,string> mp;

mp[1] = "Pavan";
mp[2] = "Rahul";

for(auto& [key,value] : mp)
{
    cout << key << " " << value << endl;
}

Instead of

for(auto& it : mp)
{
    cout << it.first << " " << it.second << endl;
}

This is one of the most common interview examples.

-----------------------------------------

9. By Value vs By Reference

By Value

auto [id,name] = p;

Copies the values.

Changing id or name does NOT change the original pair.

-----------------------------------------

By Reference

auto& [id,name] = p;

No copy.

Changing id or name modifies the original pair.

Example

pair<int,string> p = {1,"Pavan"};

auto& [id,name] = p;

id = 100;

cout << p.first;

Output

100

-----------------------------------------

10. Advantages

• Cleaner code

• No .first/.second

• No std::get<0>()

• Better readability

• Easier iteration over maps

• Less typing

-----------------------------------------

11. Where can Structured Bindings be used?

✔ pair

✔ tuple

✔ array

✔ struct/class (with public members)

✔ map iteration

-----------------------------------------

12. Interview Questions

Q. What are Structured Bindings?

Answer

Structured Bindings are a C++17 feature that allows objects such as pairs, tuples, arrays, and structs to be unpacked into separate variables.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced Structured Bindings?

Answer

C++17

-----------------------------------------

Q. What problem do they solve?

Answer

Before C++17, we had to access pair members using .first and .second or tuple elements using std::get<>(). 
Structured Bindings provide a cleaner and more readable way to unpack these objects into named variables.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What objects support Structured Bindings?

Answer

• pair
• tuple
• array
• struct/class with public members
• map elements

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is the difference between

auto

and

auto&

with Structured Bindings?

Answer

auto creates copies of the values.

auto& creates references to the original object.

Using auto&, modifying the bound variables modifies the original object.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why are Structured Bindings useful in map iteration?

Answer

Instead of writing

for(auto& it : mp)
{
    cout << it.first << " " << it.second;
}

we can write

for(auto& [key,value] : mp)
{
    cout << key << " " << value;
}

This improves readability and eliminates the need for .first and .second.

-----------------------------------------

